      "text": "Excellent question. The image you\u0027ve provided is a classic and highly informative example of a **data stride or misalignment error**. The structured, repetitive pattern is a tell-tale sign that the raw pixel data is being read with the wrong \"pitch\" (number of bytes per pixel).\n\nLet\u0027s break down the problem and the solution.\n\n### The Diagnosis\n\nThe issue is almost certainly that **your code is performing the 3-channel (RGB) to 4-channel (RGBA) conversion on data that is *already* in a 4-channel (RGBA) format.**\n\nHeres why that creates the exact pattern you\u0027re seeing:\n\nImagine your source data is already RGBA: `[R0, G0, B0, A0, R1, G1, B1, A1, ...]`\n\nYour conversion loop, however, *thinks* it\u0027s RGB. It expects to read 3 bytes, then the next pixel starts immediately after.\n\n*   **Pixel 0:** The loop reads 3 bytes starting at index 0: `R0, G0, B0`. It correctly writes `R0, G0, B0, 255` to the destination.\n*   **Pixel 1:** The loop advances its source pointer by 3. The next read starts at index 3 of the source data, which is actually `A0` (the alpha of the first pixel). The loop reads 3 bytes: `A0, R1, G1`. It incorrectly interprets these as the R, G, and B of the second pixel and writes `A0, R1, G1, 255` to the destination.\n*   **Pixel 2:** The loop advances its source pointer by another 3 (to index 6). The next read starts at `B1`. It reads `B1, A1, R2`. It writes these as `B1, A1, R2, 255`.\n\nThis creates a consistent \"skew\" in the data. Each new pixel read is shifted by one byte relative to the actual pixel data, resulting in the diagonal line artifacts and incorrect colors. The original structure of the image is completely lost and replaced by this new, incorrect pattern.\n\n### The Solution\n\nThe solution is to ensure your `if/else` logic correctly identifies the number of channels from the QOI header and **only** runs the conversion loop when the source is actually 3-channel RGB.\n\nYour image loading and texture creation logic should look exactly like the robust example from the previous answer. Let\u0027s review the critical part:\n\n```nim\n// 1. Load the QOI image.\nlet qoiImage \u003d readQOI(\"your_image_file.qoi\")\n\n// Add this line for debugging to be 100% sure!\necho \"Loaded QOI image with channels: \", qoiImage.header.channels \n\n// 2. Prepare the pixel data based on the actual channel count.\nvar finalPixelData: seq[byte]\nvar finalPixelFormat: sg_pixel_format\n\n# This is the crucial logic block.\n# Ensure your code correctly branches here.\nif qoiImage.header.channels \u003d\u003d RGBA:\n  # The data is already RGBA. DO NOT CONVERT IT.\n  # Use it directly.\n  echo \"Image is RGBA. Using data directly.\"\n  finalPixelData \u003d qoiImage.data\n  finalPixelFormat \u003d SG_PIXELFORMAT_RGBA8\nelse: # This block runs ONLY for RGB images\n  # The data is RGB. Perform the 3-to-4 channel conversion.\n  echo \"Image is RGB. Converting to RGBA...\"\n  let numPixels \u003d qoiImage.header.width.int * qoiImage.header.height.int\n  finalPixelData \u003d newSeq[byte](numPixels * 4)\n\n  var srcIndex \u003d 0\n  var dstIndex \u003d 0\n  for i in 0 ..\u003c numPixels:\n    finalPixelData[dstIndex+0] \u003d qoiImage.data[srcIndex+0] # R\n    finalPixelData[dstIndex+1] \u003d qoiImage.data[srcIndex+1] # G\n    finalPixelData[dstIndex+2] \u003d qoiImage.data[srcIndex+2] # B\n    finalPixelData[dstIndex+3] \u003d 255.byte                  # A\n    srcIndex +\u003d 3\n    dstIndex +\u003d 4\n  \n  finalPixelFormat \u003d SG_PIXELFORMAT_RGBA8\n\n// 3. Create the Sokol image using the correctly prepared data.\nvar imageDesc \u003d sg_image_desc(\n  width: qoiImage.header.width.int32,\n  height: qoiImage.header.height.int32,\n  pixel_format: finalPixelFormat, # This will always be RGBA8\n  # ... other params ...\n)\nimageDesc.data.subimage[0][0] \u003d sg_range(finalPixelData)\nlet my_sokol_image \u003d sg_make_image(imageDesc)\n```\n\n### Debugging Checklist\n\nTo fix your code, follow these steps:\n\n1.  **Verify the Source:** Add the `echo qoiImage.header.channels` line right after you load the image. Run your program. It will most likely print `RGBA`.\n2.  **Check Your `if` Condition:** This will confirm that your code is incorrectly entering the `else` block (the conversion block) when it should be entering the `if` block (the direct-use block).\n3.  **Correct The Logic:** Make sure your `if/else` statement is exactly as shown above, correctly branching based on the header information.\n\nBy ensuring you only convert what needs to be converted, your `finalPixelData` will have the correct content and your texture will render properly.",
